            "title": "Wine Microbiology",
            "abstract": [
                "The partnership between industrial microbiologists, the industries they serve, and the microbes upon which they rely is (or should be) a close one. Brewers, bakers, and those involved in fermented dairy products come to mind as being leaders in this regard. By comparison, the wine industry, with the notable exception of a few technologically astute wineries world\u00ad wide, has historically given relatively little attention to this crucial step in processing. In the last two decades, this pattern has reversed itself and the rank and file of winemaking personnel have become more intensely inter\u00ad ested in the subject of wine microbiology. Several reasons come to mind that, in part, account for this. First, prior to the late seventies, much of the research in the area of wine microbiology (particularly, the malolactic fermentation) had yet to crystalize to yield a cohesive enough picture to be of value to the winemaker. During this period and into the early eighties, the U. S. wine industry began to utilize lower levels of sulfur dioxide than did their predecessors-the goal being to reduce input of chemicals and to minimize concerns from an increasingly health conscious population of consumers. Unfortunately, the practice had a significant downside; micro\u00ad organisms that had previously been controlled suddenly reemerged as sig\u00ad nificant threats to wine production.",
                "1: The Lactic Acid Bacteria -- 2: Acetic Acid Bacteria -- 3: Yeasts and Molds -- 4: Prefermentation Processing -- 5: Fermentation and Post-Fermentation Processing -- 6: Bottling -- 7: Winery Sanitation -- Appendix A: Basic Microscopy and Laboratory Setup -- A.1 Microscope -- Magnification -- Resolution -- Contrast -- A.2 Centrifuge/Filters -- A.3 Autoclave -- A.4 Incubator -- A.5 Waterbaths -- A.6 Disposable Versus Reusable Pipettes -- A.7 Media -- A.8 Miscellaneous Supplies -- A.9 Alternatives -- Appendix B: Media Preparation and Transfer Techniques -- B.1 Introduction -- B.2 Physical/Chemical Requirements for Media -- B.2.1 Utilizable Source of Carbon and Nitrogen -- B.2.2 Oxygen Requirements -- B.2.3 Hydrogen Ion Concentration (pH) -- B.2.5 Incubation Temperature -- B.3 Sterilization of Laboratory Media and Supplies -- B.3.1 Steam Sterilization -- B.3.2 Boiling Water -- B.3.3 Dry Heat -- B.3.4 Sterile Filtration -- B.3.5 Chemical Sterilization -- Ethylene Oxide -- Dimethyldicarbonate -- Ethanol -- B.4 Media Preparation -- B.4.1 Fermentation Broths -- B.4.2 Solidified Media -- Plates -- Slants (Slopes) -- Agar Deeps -- B.5 Sterile Transfer Techniques -- B.5.1 Transfers from Plate to Plate (\u201cStreaking for Isolation\u201d) -- B.5.2 Transfer from Slant to Slant -- B.5.3 Transfer Between Agar \u201cDeeps\u201d -- B.5.4 Transfer from Plates to Liquids -- B.5.5 Liquid-to-Liquid and Liquid-to-Solid Transfers (Using Pipettes) -- Appendix C: Estimation of Population Density -- C.1 Introduction -- C.2 Preparation of Dilutions -- C.3 Population Measurements (Plating or Indirect Methods) -- C.3.1 Pour-Plate Technique -- C.3.2 Spread-Plate Technique -- C.3.3 Membrane Filtration -- C.4 Microscopic (Direct) Examination Using Viability Stains -- C.4.1 Methylene blue -- C.4.2 Ponceau-S -- C.4.3 Walford\u2019s stain -- C.4.4 Viable Cell Counting -- C.4.5 Epifluorescence Methods -- C.4.6 Bioluminescence -- C.5 Recent Technology -- C.5.1 Immunochemical Technique